#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:4
msgid "Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:6
msgid ""
"This document discusses using various kinds of authentication with Requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:8
msgid ""
"Many web services require authentication, and there are many different "
"types. Below, we outline various forms of authentication available in "
"Requests, from the simple to the complex."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:14
msgid "Basic Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:16
msgid ""
"Many web services that require authentication accept HTTP Basic Auth. This "
"is the simplest kind, and Requests supports it straight out of the box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:19
msgid "Making requests with HTTP Basic Auth is very simple::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:21
msgid ""
">>> from requests.auth import HTTPBasicAuth\n"
">>> basic = HTTPBasicAuth('user', 'pass')\n"
">>> requests.get('https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/user/pass', auth=basic)\n"
"<Response [200]>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:26
msgid ""
"In fact, HTTP Basic Auth is so common that Requests provides a handy "
"shorthand for using it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:29
msgid ""
">>> requests.get('https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/user/pass', auth=('user', "
"'pass'))\n"
"<Response [200]>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:32
msgid ""
"Providing the credentials in a tuple like this is exactly the same as the "
"``HTTPBasicAuth`` example above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:37
msgid "netrc Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:39
msgid ""
"If no authentication method is given with the ``auth`` argument, Requests "
"will attempt to get the authentication credentials for the URL's hostname "
"from the user's netrc file. The netrc file overrides raw HTTP authentication "
"headers set with `headers=`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:44
msgid ""
"If credentials for the hostname are found, the request is sent with HTTP "
"Basic Auth."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:47
msgid ""
"Requests will search for the netrc file at `~/.netrc`, `~/_netrc`, or at the "
"path specified by the `NETRC` environment variable. `~` denotes the user's "
"home directory, which is `$HOME` on Unix based systems and `%USERPROFILE%` "
"on Windows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:51
msgid ""
"Usage of netrc file can be disabled by setting `trust_env` to `False` in the "
"Requests session::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:54
msgid ""
">>> s = requests.Session()\n"
">>> s.trust_env = False\n"
">>> s.get('https://httpbin.org/basic-auth/user/pass')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:59
msgid "Digest Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:61
msgid ""
"Another very popular form of HTTP Authentication is Digest Authentication, "
"and Requests supports this out of the box as well::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:64
msgid ""
">>> from requests.auth import HTTPDigestAuth\n"
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/digest-auth/auth/user/pass'\n"
">>> requests.get(url, auth=HTTPDigestAuth('user', 'pass'))\n"
"<Response [200]>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:71
msgid "OAuth 1 Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:73
msgid ""
"A common form of authentication for several web APIs is OAuth. The "
"``requests-oauthlib`` library allows Requests users to easily make OAuth 1 "
"authenticated requests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:76
msgid ""
">>> import requests\n"
">>> from requests_oauthlib import OAuth1\n"
"\n"
">>> url = 'https://api.twitter.com/1.1/account/verify_credentials.json'\n"
">>> auth = OAuth1('YOUR_APP_KEY', 'YOUR_APP_SECRET',\n"
"...               'USER_OAUTH_TOKEN', 'USER_OAUTH_TOKEN_SECRET')\n"
"\n"
">>> requests.get(url, auth=auth)\n"
"<Response [200]>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:86
msgid ""
"For more information on how to OAuth flow works, please see the official "
"`OAuth`_ website. For examples and documentation on requests-oauthlib, "
"please see the `requests_oauthlib`_ repository on GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:91
msgid "OAuth 2 and OpenID Connect Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:93
msgid ""
"The ``requests-oauthlib`` library also handles OAuth 2, the authentication "
"mechanism underpinning OpenID Connect. See the `requests-oauthlib OAuth2 "
"documentation`_ for details of the various OAuth 2 credential management "
"flows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:97
msgid "`Web Application Flow`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:98
msgid "`Mobile Application Flow`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:99
msgid "`Legacy Application Flow`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:100
msgid "`Backend Application Flow`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:103
msgid "Other Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:105
msgid ""
"Requests is designed to allow other forms of authentication to be easily and "
"quickly plugged in. Members of the open-source community frequently write "
"authentication handlers for more complicated or less commonly-used forms of "
"authentication. Some of the best have been brought together under the "
"`Requests organization`_, including:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:111
msgid "Kerberos_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:112
msgid "NTLM_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:114
msgid ""
"If you want to use any of these forms of authentication, go straight to "
"their GitHub page and follow the instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:119
msgid "New Forms of Authentication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:121
msgid ""
"If you can't find a good implementation of the form of authentication you "
"want, you can implement it yourself. Requests makes it easy to add your own "
"forms of authentication."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:125
msgid ""
"To do so, subclass :class:`AuthBase <requests.auth.AuthBase>` and implement "
"the ``__call__()`` method::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:128
msgid ""
">>> import requests\n"
">>> class MyAuth(requests.auth.AuthBase):\n"
"...     def __call__(self, r):\n"
"...         # Implement my authentication\n"
"...         return r\n"
"...\n"
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/get'\n"
">>> requests.get(url, auth=MyAuth())\n"
"<Response [200]>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:138
msgid ""
"When an authentication handler is attached to a request, it is called during "
"request setup. The ``__call__`` method must therefore do whatever is "
"required to make the authentication work. Some forms of authentication will "
"additionally add hooks to provide further functionality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/authentication.rst:143
msgid ""
"Further examples can be found under the `Requests organization`_ and in the "
"``auth.py`` file."
msgstr ""
